Applied Stats Project¶

Dataset - Insurance Info (Anonymized)¶

</strong> Attributes:

  • age: age of primary beneficiary
  • sex: insurance contractor gender, female, male
  • bmi: Body mass index, providing an understanding of body, weights that are relatively high or low relative to height, objective index of body weight (kg / m ^ 2) using the ratio of height to weight, ideally 18.5 to 24.9
  • children: Number of children covered by health insurance / Number of dependents
  • smoker: Smokingregion: the beneficiary's residential area in the US, northeast, southeast, southwest, northwest.
  • charges: Individual medical costs billed by health insurance.

In [10]:
df[['age', 'bmi', 'charges']].skew(axis = 0) # 3.f. Measure of Skew
Out[10]:
age        0.055673
bmi        0.284047
charges    1.515880
dtype: float64

Charges has much higher value of skew as expected from seeing the distributions

Skewness is a measure of symmetry in a distribution. Actually, its more correct to describe it as a measure of lack of symmetry.
It's a measure of asymmetry of the probability distribution of a real-valued random variable about its mean.
A standard normal distribution is perfectly symmetrical and has zero skew.
Pandas dataframe.skew() function return unbiased skew over requested axis Normalized by N-1.

4. Hypothesis Testing¶

4.a. Do charges of people who smoke differ significantly from the people who don't?¶

In [29]:
sns.set()
plt.figure(figsize = [10, 7])
sns.boxplot(data = df, y = 'charges', x = 'smoker', color = '#5aa2ce')
plt.show()
In [30]:
sns.set()
plt.figure(figsize = [10, 7])
sns.histplot(df[df.smoker == 'yes']["charges"] , color="skyblue", label="Charges for Smokers", kde = True)
sns.histplot(df[df.smoker == 'no']["charges"] , color="red", label="Charges for Non Smokers", kde = True)
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Visually, we can infer that the premium charges are definitely higher for smokers than non-smokers
We should conduct a hypothesis test (t-test) for the differences in means across the two smokers and non-smoker charges to test.

H 0 : μ s = μ ns
H a : μ s ≠ μ ns
In [31]:
charges_smokers = df[df.smoker == 'yes']['charges']
charges_non_smokers = df[df.smoker == 'no']['charges']
In [32]:
charges_smokers.mean()
Out[32]:
32050.23183153285
In [33]:
charges_non_smokers.mean()
Out[33]:
8434.268297856199
In [34]:
t_stat, p_value = ttest_ind(charges_smokers, charges_non_smokers)
print(f'T Statistic: {t_stat} | P Value: {p_value}')

T Statistic: 46.664921172723716 | P Value: 8.271435842177219e-283

The P Value for the ttest is 8.271e-283 which is far less than a level of signifance of: 0.05. (p-value is the observed probability of the null hypothesis to happen) So, we can reject the null hypothesis that the charges both smokers and non smokers have equal means. The charges do signifcantly differ.

In [38]:
bmi_males.mean()
Out[38]:
30.943128698224832
In [39]:
bmi_females.mean()
Out[39]:
30.377749244713023
In [40]:
t_stat, p_value = ttest_ind(bmi_males, bmi_females)
print(f'T Statistic: {t_stat} | P Value: {p_value}')

T Statistic: 1.696752635752224 | P Value: 0.08997637178984932

The P Value for the two samples t test for bmi across males and females is 0.0899 which is greater than 0.05. So,we fail to reject the null hypothesis that the two samples have equal means. Hence, The BMI of males and females do not differ significantly.

4.c. Is the proportion of smokers significantly different in different genders?¶

In [41]:

In [42]:
female_smokers = df[df['sex'] == 'female'].smoker.value_counts()[1]  # number of female smokers
male_smokers = df[df['sex'] == 'male'].smoker.value_counts()[1] # number of male smokers
n_females = df.sex.value_counts()[1] # number of females in the data
n_males = df.sex.value_counts()[0] #number of males in the data
In [43]:
print([female_smokers, male_smokers] , [n_females, n_males])
print(f' Proportion of smokers in females, males = {round(115/662,2)}%, {round(159/676,2)}% respectively')

[115, 159] [662, 676]
 Proportion of smokers in females, males = 0.17%, 0.24% respectively
In [44]:
stat, p_value = proportions_ztest([female_smokers, male_smokers] , [n_females, n_males])
print(f'Z Statistic: {t_stat} | P Value: {p_value}')

Z Statistic: 1.696752635752224 | P Value: 0.005324114164320532

P Value is 0.005 which is less than 0.05; Hence, we reject the null hypothesis that the proportions are equal. So, the proportions of smokers across both genders differ significantly.

sns.histplot(bmi_two_children, color="lime", label="BMI | Two Children", kde = True)
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Testing multiple sample means using ANOVA

In [48]:
df_three = df[df.children <= 2]
In [49]:
mod = ols('bmi ~ children', data = df_three).fit()
sm.stats.anova_lm(mod, typ=2)
Out[49]:
sum_sq df F PR(>F)
children 27.272296 1.0 0.719586 0.396458
Residual 43054.351120 1136.0 NaN NaN

p value is 0.396458 and it is not less than our chosen level of signifance at 5%. So, we fail to reject the null hypothesis at 5% level of significance that all three distributions have equal means. Hence, BMI across females with 0, 1, or, 2 children does not differ significantly.
